snippet.textDisplay:
5:40
I just had to research this for an assignment:

Many species in polar marine systems such as flatfish, some cod species, have an anti-freezing adaptation to the cold. Particularly in water with a high salt-concentration, it’s freezing point lowers to -2°C, which is much colder than the freezing point of bodily-fluids for most species. To combat this, these fish produce antifreeze-molecules (glycoproteins) which reduces the freezing point of their bodily fluids, and as a result prevents their blood from crystalizing; allowing them to survive in this extreme environment.
- Copied and pasted from my abstract.
In case anyone was wondering :)
